observations.recommendation:
We recommended Management the following:

Assess whether there is a need to reconstitute the composition of the Inventory Committee to ensure that the task shall be completed;

Conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances in accordance with the guidelines and procedures set forth in COA Circular No. 2020-006;

Prepare the Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) using the prescribed format upon completion of the physical and furnish the Auditor concerned with the copy thereafter; and    

Conduct reconciliation between inventory count per RPCPPE and property and accounting records, as warranted.

Recommendation
We recommended and Management agreed, though the GFPS to:
Attend the GAD Planning, Budgeting, and Auditing (GAD PBA) Seminar to be conducted by COA Regional Office No. IX on November 18–20, 2025;
Coordinate with the Municipal Local Government Operations Office (MLGOO) for the conduct of GAD capability trainings/workshop, specifically on the establishment of a GAD Database to include sex-disaggregated data and the use of the HGDG tool;
Establish and maintain a GAD database that SDD to assist in the identification and prioritization of gender issues within the LGU; and
Administer HGDG design checklist (Box 7a and 7b) and PIMME checklist (Box 16 and 17) on major programs and projects to assess the gender-responsiveness and determine the actual GAD-attributable cost and submit the accomplished checklists with supporting documentation to COA and DILG for proper review and evaluation

We recommended Management to direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Prepare the corresponding adjusting entry to record the cash deposits made by the Municipal Treasurer in the total amount of ₱1,100.00;

Prepare the corresponding adjusting entry to record the bank charges incurred on the bank account with below the maintaining balance;

Conduct a thorough analysis to determine the nature of the unidentified credit memo of ₱3,590.00 and prepare the corresponding adjusting entry thereafter; and

Ensure that all reconciling items identified during the subsequent preparation of bank reconciliation shall be adjusted immediately.

We recommended management the following:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the claims of various officers and employees to Due to Officers and Employees account;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct a thorough analysis on the item Listed as “Others” to determine whether the same shall qualify as part of the accounts payable based on the recognition criteria for liabilities, otherwise cause the necessary adjustment;

Moving forward, direct the Municipal Accountant to exercise due professional care in the recording of account payable taking into consideration the completeness and propriety of supporting documents; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to incorporate the separate schedule prepared in the notes to the financial statements and provide other relevant information as deemed necessary.

We recommended and Management agreed to comply the following:
Assess whether there is a need to reconstitute the composition of the Inventory Committee to ensure that the task shall be completed;
Conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances in accordance with the guidelines and procedures set forth in COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Prepare of the RPCPPE using the prescribed format upon completion of the physical count and furnish the Auditor concerned with the copy thereafter; and
Conduct reconciliation between inventory count per RPCPPE and property and accounting records, as warranted.

We recommended and Management agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Prepare the corresponding adjusting entry to record the cash deposits made by the Municipal Treasurer in the total amount of ₱1,100.00;
Prepare the corresponding adjusting entry to record the bank charges incurred on the bank account with below the maintaining balance;
Conduct a thorough analysis to determine the nature of the unidentified credit memo of ₱3,590.00 and prepare the corresponding adjusting entry thereafter; and
Ensure that all reconciling items identified during the subsequent preparation of bank reconciliation shall be adjusted immediately.

We recommended management the following:

Direct the Office of the Municipal Treasurer in coordination with the Office of the Municipal Assessor to conduct reconciliation of records in order to update the taxpayer’s index card particularly on assessed value of real properties and other relevant data. Thereafter, reconciliation shall be made regularly at the close of each year;

Direct the Office of the Municipal Treasurer to maintain a readily available monitoring flatform matching every collection made with the corresponding year of receivables;

Direct the Office of the Municipal Accountant to extend the analysis made and come up with a schedule showing the details of RPT/SET receivables on yearly basis;

Direct the Office of the Municipal Accountant to make a subsidiary ledger (SL) for RPT/SET receivable using the year when the receivable was recorded as code starting CY 2023;

Reconciliation of record between the monitoring schedule prepared by the Office of the Municipal Treasurer and SL prepared by the Office of the Municipal Accountant at the close of each year; and

Direct the Office of the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjusting entry to correct the understatement of RPT/SET receivable and corresponding understatement of Deferred Real Property Tax Income/ Deferred Special Education Tax Income.

We recommended management the following:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjustment to correct the erroneous entry made to close the related income account to government equity;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to modify the subsidiary ledger by year to monitor the corresponding disbursement, if any;

Moving forward, direct the Municipal Accountant to provide the necessary disclosures in the notes to the financial statement relative to the Trust Liabilities – Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund account; and

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to ensure the actual transfer of unexpected DRRM fund to the trust fund account at the close of the year.

We recommended management the following:

Direct the personnel in-charge in the preparation of remittances to financial institution to trace whom the over remittances were made;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the debit balance of other payable totaling ₱5,876.50 to its proper account Due from Officers and Employees;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the amount due to DSWD relative to the Poverty Alleviation Program (SEA Loan); the 20% share for the Tuition Fee relative to the operation of WMSU – ESU Diplahan Campus; and the collection arising from the sale of bid documents amounting to ₱460,710.65, ₱994,896.87 and ₱946,086.13 respectively to trust liabilities;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to undertake a thorough analysis in coordination with the concerned offices relative to the cash balance of trust receipts.

We recommended management to adhere with the proper recording of purchases by:
directing the personnel in charged in the preparation of SSMI to submit the same on a weekly basis;
directing the Municipal Accountant to stop the practice of recording regular purchases as direct expenses but instead record it as inventory items and expenses only upon receipt of the SSMI.
